  "text": {
    "title": "Unit Four: The Present Tense of Essere and Avere",
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Present Tense of Essere and Avere",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "4.01",
            "content": "Like their counterparts in many other languages, the Italian verbs **essere** (to be) and **avere** (to have) are irregular. Here are the forms of the **present tense**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["", "Essere", "", "Avere", ""],
              "rows": [
                ["(**io**)", "**sono**", "I am", "**ho**", "I have/have got"],
                ["(**tu**)", "**sei**", "you [sing.] are", "**hai**", "you [sing.] have/have got"],
                ["(**lui/lei**)", "**è**", "he/she/it is", "**ha**", "he/she/it has/has got"],
                ["(**noi**)", "**siamo**", "we are", "**abbiamo**", "we have/have got"],
                ["(**voi**)", "**siete**", "you [pl.] are", "**avete**", "you [pl.] have/have got"],
                ["(**loro**)", "**sono**", "they are", "**hanno**", "they have/have got"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "As shown in the examples, it is not usually necessary to use the **subject pronouns** before the verb since the forms for the different persons are different – **sei** can only be **second person singular** (**tu**), **siete** can only be **second person plural** (**voi**), etc. Even with **sono**, the context always shows whether it means ‘**I am**’ or ‘**they are**’."
          },
          {
            "content": "The pronoun is only required for emphasis, or to mark a contrast:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**Sono** medico.", "I’m a doctor."],
                ["**Siamo** cugini.", "We are cousins."],
                ["**Siete** stranieri.", "You are foreigners."],
                ["**Paola** e **Anna** **sono** alte.", "Paola and Anna are tall."],
                ["**Claudio** è **mio fratello**.", "Claudio is my brother."],
                ["**Ho** un cellulare.", "I’ve got a mobile phone."],
                ["**Hai** il mio indirizzo.", "You have my address."],
                ["**Hanno** un esame.", "They have an exam."],
                ["**Anna** **ha** una chitarra nuova.", "Anna’s got a new guitar."],
                ["**Io** **sono** medico e **lui** è insegnante.", "I’m a doctor and he’s a teacher."],
                ["**Tu** **hai** una bella bici, ma **io** **ho** una macchina.", "You’ve got a nice bike, but I’ve got a car."]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Subject Pronouns",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "4.02",
            "content": "The Italian **subject pronouns** are:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Person", "Singular", "", "Plural", ""],
              "rows": [
                ["1st", "**io**", "I", "**noi**", "we"],
                ["2nd", "**tu**", "you", "**voi**", "you"],
                ["3rd", "**lui**", "he", "**loro**", "they"],
                ["3rd", "**lei**", "she", "", ""]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "For the **third person**, the following pronouns can still be found in some texts, but are not normally used in contemporary Italian:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Singular", "Plural", "Notes"],
              "rows": [
                ["**egli** [m], **esso** [m]", "", "instead of the singular **lui**"],
                ["**ella** [f], **essa** [f]", "", "instead of the singular **lei**"],
                ["", "**essi** [m], **esse** [f]", "instead of the plural **loro**"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "**Lui** (**third person singular** pronoun) replaces a **masculine** noun (like the English ‘**he**’); **lei** replaces a **feminine** noun (like the English ‘**she**’)."
          },
          {
            "content": "**Lui**, **lei** and **loro** are only used to refer to persons. In referring to objects, Italian normally avoids using the obsolete forms **esso**, **essa**, **essi**, **esse**, and omits the pronoun altogether:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**Lui** è **Paolo**, **lei** è **Anna**.", "He is Paolo, she is Anna."],
                ["‘Cos’è?’ ‘È una chiave.’", "‘What is it?’ ‘It’s a key.’"],
                ["È **la chitarra** di **Anna**.", "It’s Anna’s guitar."],
                ["**Sono** **i libri** di **Paolo**.", "They are Paolo’s books."]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Interrogative Form",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "4.03",
            "content": "The **interrogative** is formed by adding a question mark at the end of the sentence:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**Sei** pronto?", "Are you ready?"],
                ["**Siete** stranieri?", "Are you foreigners?"],
                ["**Hai** il mio indirizzo?", "Have you got my address?"],
                ["**Avete** amici italiani?", "Have you any Italian friends?"],
                ["**Hanno** un esame?", "Have they got an exam?"]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Negative Form",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "4.04",
            "content": "The **negative** is formed by putting **non** (i.e. ‘not’) before the verb:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**Claudio** **non** è **mio fratello**.", "Claudio is not my brother."],
                ["**Non** **siamo** italiani.", "We’re not Italian."],
                ["**Non** **siete** stranieri?", "Aren’t you foreigners?"],
                ["**Non** **hai** il mio indirizzo?", "Haven’t you got my address?"],
                ["**Non** **hanno** un esame.", "They don’t have an exam."],
                ["**Non** **abbiamo** amici italiani.", "We haven’t got any Italian friends."],
                ["**Non** **ho** la minima idea di cosa regalare a **Paola**.", "I haven’t the slightest idea what to give Paola."]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Formal Form",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "4.05",
            "content": "In Italian there is a **formal** way of addressing people which is used with people we do not know, or when some degree of formality is required. When the **formal** form is required, the pronoun used for the **singular**, for both men and women, is **Lei** (**third person singular**); the pronoun used for the **plural** is normally **Voi**, but in situations when a high degree of formality is required **Loro** can be used:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**Lei** è molto gentile, **Signore**.", "You’re very kind(, Sir)."],
                ["**Lei** **non** è troppo alta, **Signora**!", "You’re not too tall(, Madam)!"],
                ["**Signora Belli**, (**Lei**) **ha** la patente?", "Mrs Belli, have you got a driving licence?"],
                ["**Professore**, (**Lei**) **ha** tempo?", "Have you got time(, Professor/Sir)?"],
                ["**Signor Neri**, (**Lei**) è pronto?", "Mr Neri, are you ready?"],
                ["**Signori Conti**, (**Voi**) **siete** italiani?", "Mr and Mrs Conti, are you Italian?"],
                ["(**Signori Conti**, **Loro** **sono** italiani?)", "Mr and Mrs Conti, are you Italian?"]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Spelling",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "4.06",
            "content": "There are some spelling mistakes involving **essere** and **avere** which are commonly made by learners; be careful to remember the following differences:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Correct", "Incorrect", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**è**", "e", "he/she/it is"],
                ["**ho**", "o", "I have"],
                ["**hai**", "ai", "you have"],
                ["**ha**", "a", "he/she/it has"],
                ["**hanno**", "anno", "they have"]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Use of Essere and Avere",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "4.07",
            "content": "The verbs **essere** and **avere** are normally used as the verbs ‘**to be**’ and ‘**to have**’ are used in English. **Essere** is usually followed by an **adjective** or a **noun**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**Siete** studenti?", "Are you students?"],
                ["**Daniela** è medico.", "Daniela is a doctor."],
                ["**Tu** e **Anna** **siete** cugini?", "Are you and Anna cousins?"],
                ["**Siete** gentili!", "You are kind!"],
                ["**Gli amici** di **Paul** **sono** italiani.", "Paul’s friends are Italian."]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "**Avere** is normally followed by a **noun** (or a **noun** accompanied by an **adjective**):",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**Hai** il libro?", "Have you got the book?"],
                ["**Non** **ho** tempo.", "I haven’t time."],
                ["**Abbiamo** molti amici.", "We have a lot of friends."],
                ["**Hanno** una casa grande.", "They have a big house."],
                ["**Paolo** e **io** **abbiamo** una macchina.", "Paolo and I have got a car."]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "4.08",
            "content": "The verb **avere**, followed by a **noun**, is also used in a number of **idiomatic expressions** which correspond to English expressions using ‘**to be**’ followed by an **adjective** or an **adverbial phrase**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**avere caldo**", "to be hot"],
                ["**avere fame**", "to be hungry"],
                ["**avere freddo**", "to be cold"],
                ["**avere paura**", "to be afraid"],
                ["**avere ragione**", "to be right"],
                ["**avere sete**", "to be thirsty"],
                ["**avere sonno**", "to be sleepy"],
                ["**avere torto**", "to be wrong"],
                ["**avere fretta**", "to be in a hurry"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**Abbiamo** fame.", "We are hungry."],
                ["**Avete** ragione!", "You’re right!"],
                ["**Marina** **ha** fretta.", "Marina is in a hurry."],
                ["(**Lei**) **ha** sete, **Signora**?", "Are you thirsty(, Madam)?"],
                ["**Non** **hai** freddo, **Claudia**?", "Aren’t you cold, Claudia?"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "4.09",
            "content": "**Avere** is also used in Italian to express age:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**Francesca** **ha** 17 anni.", "Francesca is 17 (years old)."],
                ["**Il figlio** di **Gianni** **ha** un anno.", "Gianni’s son is one."],
                ["Quanti anni **hai**?", "How old are you?"]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "C’è and Ci Sono",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "4.10",
            "content": "The verb **essere** is used in the expressions **c’è** (**there is**) followed by a **singular noun**, and **ci sono** (**there are**) followed by a **plural noun**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**C’è** una lettera per te.", "There’s a letter for you."],
                ["**C’è** poco tempo.", "There’s little/not much time."],
                ["**C’è** molto tempo!", "There’s plenty of time!"],
                ["**C’è** un problema.", "There’s a problem."],
                ["**Ci sono** due ingressi.", "There are two entrances."],
                ["Nel negozio **ci sono** molti clienti.", "There are a lot of customers in the shop."]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "4.11",
            "content": "Note that **c’è** and **ci sono** are not usually emphatic. So, in the English sentences in paragraph 4.10, the voice stress does not fall on ‘**there**’, but on the **noun** that follows it (i.e. on ‘**letter**’, ‘**little/plenty of time**’, ‘**problem**’, etc.). Thus **c’è** and **ci sono** sometimes do not correspond to ‘**there is**’ or ‘**there are**’, as in the following examples:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**C’è** **Luisa** al telefono. [i.e. she has just rung]", "Luisa’s on the phone. [not: There’s Luisa on the phone.]"],
                ["**Ci sono** **i tuoi amici** che ti aspettano. [i.e. they have just arrived]", "Your friends are waiting for you. [not: There are your friends waiting for you.]"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "4.12",
            "content": "The **interrogative** is formed by simply adding a question mark at the end of the sentence, or with a ‘**question word**’ (see Unit 9):",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**C’è** **il Professor Gatti**?", "Is Professor Gatti there/anywhere/around? [i.e. I’d like to see/talk to Professor Gatti.]"],
                ["**C’è** molto traffico?", "Is there a lot of traffic?"],
                ["Quanti ingressi **ci sono**?", "How many entrances are there?"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "4.13",
            "content": "The **negative** is formed by placing **non** before **c’è** or **ci sono**:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Italian", "English"],
              "rows": [
                ["**Non** **c’è** tempo.", "There is no time."],
                ["Domani **non** **c’è** lezione.", "There is no class tomorrow."],
                ["**Non** **ci sono** clienti.", "There aren’t any customers."]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "* In Italian the **double negative** is used: **non** + **nessuno**."
          },
          {
            "id": "4.14",
            "content": "Note that in **negative** sentences giving general information, it is more usual to use the **plural** **non ci sono** than the **singular** **non c’è**."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
